00:22:26,640 --> 00:22:29,520
There. Let's reconcile them.

261
00:22:32,800 --> 00:22:34,800
There. Not bad, eh?

262
00:22:38,520 --> 00:22:43,760
Dad, if you found a precious relic from your childhood,

263
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:47,520
how would it make you feel? Happy? Sad? Nostalgic? What?

264
00:22:48,560 --> 00:22:50,960
I didn't have this gnome when I was a child.

265
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:54,480
He was a retirement gift from my old regiment.

266
00:22:54,520 --> 00:22:58,800
No, I mean something you hid like a secret treasure.

267
00:23:00,280 --> 00:23:02,280
I should varnish him before autumn.

268
00:23:06,040 --> 00:23:08,560
I'll make some tea. Do you want some?

269
00:23:08,600 --> 00:23:10,600
Breathe in. Hold still.

270
00:23:12,600 --> 00:23:14,240
Better now?

271
00:23:14,280 --> 00:23:16,080
Shut the door!

272
00:23:16,120 --> 00:23:18,080
There's a howling gale.

273
00:23:18,120 --> 00:23:20,040
It's hardly Siberia.

274
00:23:20,080 --> 00:23:22,560
I can see you're not allergic

275
00:23:22,600 --> 00:23:27,080
to car fumes. I almost coughed up my pleura last night.

276
00:23:27,120 --> 00:23:28,560
Coughed up a pleura? Sure.

277
00:23:28,600 --> 00:23:32,040
- What's on the menu today, Suzanne? - Endives au gratin.

278
00:23:32,080 --> 00:23:34,440
They'll have you on your knees, you'll see.

279
00:23:34,480 --> 00:23:35,640
They're good, then?

280
00:23:35,680 --> 00:23:37,800
- Depends where. - If it's at the toilet...

281
00:23:37,840 --> 00:23:39,080
Not good!

282
00:23:44,400 --> 00:23:48,200
12:15, laughs orgasmically to attract alpha male.

283
00:23:48,240 --> 00:23:51,040
He's going to drive me berserk!

284
00:23:51,080 --> 00:23:54,680
Can't he give up? There are plenty of other bars.

285
00:23:54,720 --> 00:23:56,600
Goodbye.

286
00:23:56,640 --> 00:23:57,840
Suzanne.

287
00:23:57,880 --> 00:23:59,720
- Suzanne. - Yes.

288
00:23:59,760 --> 00:24:02,400
"Au gratin" means white sauce, right?

289
00:24:02,440 --> 00:24:04,000
Yes, why?

290
00:24:04,040 --> 00:24:08,880
I can't stomach it. Like you and horse meat.

291
00:24:08,920 --> 00:24:11,560
It's not my stomach, it's my memory.

292
00:24:12,560 --> 00:24:14,280
I'd rather cook human flesh.

293
00:24:14,320 --> 00:24:16,280
You're kidding!

294
00:24:26,960 --> 00:24:31,160
Suzanne, would you mind if I left early today?

295
00:24:31,200 --> 00:24:33,160
What's his name?

296
00:24:33,200 --> 00:24:35,200
Dominique Bredoteau.

297
00:24:40,520 --> 00:24:42,280
Hello.

298
00:24:43,360 --> 00:24:45,200
Are you Dominique Bredoteau?

299
00:24:45,240 --> 00:24:46,560
That's me.

300
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:48,520
Why?

301
00:24:48,560 --> 00:24:50,560
It's about...

302
00:24:51,560 --> 00:24:52,760
...the petition.

303
00:24:52,800 --> 00:24:54,160
Petition?

304
00:24:54,200 --> 00:24:58,760
Yes. The petition to...

305
00:25:00,120 --> 00:25:01,960
...to canonize Lady Di.

306
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:03,600
No, thanks.

307
00:25:03,640 --> 00:25:04,640
No.

308
00:25:12,120 --> 00:25:14,600
Ladies and gentlemen, sorry to bother you...

309
00:25:19,360 --> 00:25:21,440
- Yes? - Hello.

310
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:25,000
I'm looking for Dominique Bredoteau for the European census.

311
00:25:26,120 --> 00:25:28,080
Come up. Third floor.

312
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:39,000
Hello, kitten.

313
00:25:42,240 --> 00:25:43,400
Earl Grey?

314
00:25:43,440 --> 00:25:45,440
Jasmine?

315
00:25:45,520 --> 00:25:48,400
What will you have?

316
00:25:52,160 --> 00:25:53,520
I'm working.

317
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:04,720
There. I'm coming.

318
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:08,960
Do you know where I can find Dominique Bredoteau?

319
00:26:09,040 --> 00:26:11,200
Oh, my poor dear!

320
00:26:12,280 --> 00:26:13,360
You just missed him.

321
00:26:14,400 --> 00:26:17,040
Look, there he goes now.

322
00:26:26,120 --> 00:26:27,080
Bre-to-deau.

323
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:29,880
Not Bre-do-teau.

324
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:31,720
You need

325
00:26:31,800 --> 00:26:35,120
a glass of mulled wine.

326
00:26:35,200 --> 00:26:36,920
Come in.

327
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:38,160
Come on in.

328
00:26:41,080 --> 00:26:45,520
I've lived here for five years. This is the first time we've met.

329
00:26:45,560 --> 00:26:48,200
I never go out on the landing.

330
00:26:48,280 --> 00:26:52,080
I'm fussy about who I meet.

331
00:26:52,160 --> 00:26:53,640
They're all creeps anyway.

332
00:26:55,800 --> 00:26:58,240
Come in. Here.

333
00:26:58,320 --> 00:26:59,640
Come in.

334
00:27:00,640 --> 00:27:03,080
They call me the Glass Man,

335
00:27:03,160 --> 00:27:06,560
but my name is Raymond Dufayel.

336
00:27:07,680 --> 00:27:11,800
- Amélie Poulain. I'm a waitress at... - The Two Windmills. I know.

337
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:17,680
And you've come back empty-handed from your search for Bretodeau.

338
00:27:19,160 --> 00:27:22,280
Because it's not "do", it's "to".

339
00:27:22,320 --> 00:27:24,720
- Like "Toto". - Thank you.

340
00:27:28,400 --> 00:27:30,040
I love that painting.

341
00:27:30,080 --> 00:27:32,640
It's the Luncheon Of The Boating Party.

342
00:27:34,320 --> 00:27:35,280
By Renoir.

343
00:27:40,920 --> 00:27:44,680
I've painted one each year for twenty years.

344
00:27:46,280 --> 00:27:48,880
The hardest part is the looks.

345
00:27:48,920 --> 00:27:54,760
I sometimes feel they deliberately change their mood as soon as my back's turned.

346
00:27:54,800 --> 00:27:56,360
They look quite happy there.

347
00:27:56,440 --> 00:27:58,640
They should be.

348
00:27:58,680 --> 00:28:00,640
This year they had hare with morels.

349
00:28:01,840 --> 00:28:05,280
And waffles with jam for the children.

350
00:28:05,360 --> 00:28:10,640
Now, what have I done with that piece of paper?

351
00:28:12,680 --> 00:28:17,840
Ah, you've noticed my video camera at the window.

352
00:28:17,880 --> 00:28:20,440
It's a gift from my sister-in-law.

353
00:28:20,480 --> 00:28:23,200
I put it there

354
00:28:23,280 --> 00:28:26,080
so I don't need to wind up my clocks.

355
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:29,960
After all these years,

356
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:34,160
the only person I still can't capture

357
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:36,400
is the girl with the glass of water.

358
00:28:36,440 --> 00:28:37,880
She's in the middle,

359
00:28:37,920 --> 00:28:40,640
yet she's on the outside.

360
00:28:42,200 --> 00:28:44,640
Maybe she's just different from the others.

361
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:47,400
In what way?

362
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:50,360
I don't know.

363
00:28:50,400 --> 00:28:55,400
When she was little, she can't have played much with other children.

364
00:28:57,160 --> 00:28:59,360
Maybe never.

365
00:29:02,920 --> 00:29:04,240
Here.

366
00:29:04,280 --> 00:29:08,040
Dominique Bretodeau, 27 Rue Mouffetard.

367
00:29:09,320 --> 00:29:10,520
It's for you.

368
00:29:11,720 --> 00:29:16,480
Every Tuesday morning, Dominique Bretodeau goes to buy a chicken.

369
00:29:16,560 --> 00:29:19,560
He usually roasts it and has it with sauté potatoes.

370
00:29:19,600 --> 00:29:22,760
After carving the legs, the breast and the wings,

371
00:29:22,800 --> 00:29:26,680
he loves picking the hot carcass with his fingers,

372
00:29:26,720 --> 00:29:28,320
starting with the oysters.

373
00:29:31,360 --> 00:29:35,040
But not today. Bretodeau won't buy a chicken.

374
00:29:35,080 --> 00:29:36,480
He'll go no further

375
00:29:36,520 --> 00:29:38,120
than this phone booth here.

376
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:48,800
In a flash, it all came back to him.

377
00:30:48,840 --> 00:30:51,920
Federico Bahamontes winning the Tour de France in '59.

378
00:30:54,800 --> 00:30:56,800
Aunt Josette's slips.

379
00:30:59,240 --> 00:31:02,200
And most of all, that tragic day.

380
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:07,000
That tragic day when he won all the marbles at break time.

381
00:31:15,480 --> 00:31:16,480
Bretodeau!

382
00:31:19,520 --> 00:31:20,640
Bretodeau!

383
00:31:27,720 --> 00:31:30,000
The pinch, Bretodeau!

384
00:31:30,040 --> 00:31:32,040
Do you understand, Bretodeau?

385
00:31:39,440 --> 00:31:40,760
Cognac, please.

386
00:31:45,920 --> 00:31:48,520
It's amazing, what just happened to me.

387
00:31:48,560 --> 00:31:52,600
It must be my guardian angel. It's the only explanation.

388
00:31:52,640 --> 00:31:55,000
It was as if the phone booth was calling me.

389
00:31:55,040 --> 00:31:57,360
It rang and rang.

390
00:31:59,760 --> 00:32:02,720
Same here. The microwave's calling me.

391
00:32:04,880 --> 00:32:06,880
I'll have another cognac.

392
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:16,600
Life's strange.

393
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:23,240
To a kid, time always drags. Suddenly you're 50.

394
00:32:25,320 --> 00:32:27,320
All that's left of your childhood

395
00:32:27,360 --> 00:32:29,520
fits in a little box,

396
00:32:29,560 --> 00:32:30,960
a little rusty box.

397
00:32:34,240 --> 00:32:36,680
Have you got kids, miss?

398
00:32:41,600 --> 00:32:44,120
I have a daughter. She must be about your age.

399
00:32:47,720 --> 00:32:49,640
We haven't spoken for years.

400
00:32:50,640 --> 00:32:53,480
I heard she had a child, a boy.

401
00:32:54,600 --> 00:32:55,600
His name is Lucas.

402
00:33:01,920 --> 00:33:06,280
I think it's time I looked them up before I'm in a box myself.

403
00:33:07,520 --> 00:33:08,920
Don't you think?

404
00:33:16,200 --> 00:33:20,400
Amélie suddenly has a strange feeling of complete harmony.

405
00:33:20,440 --> 00:33:26,160
It's a perfect moment. Soft light, a scent in the air, the quiet murmur of the city,

406
00:33:27,440 --> 00:33:30,520
She breathes deeply. Life seems so simple and clear.

407
00:33:30,560 --> 00:33:35,160
A surge of love, an urge to help mankind suddenly engulfs her.

408
00:33:47,040 --> 00:33:49,560
Let me help you. Step down.

409
00:33:49,600 --> 00:33:52,520
Off we go! We just passed the drum major's widow!

410
00:33:52,560 --> 00:33:55,440
She's worn his coat since the day he died. Careful.

411
00:33:55,480 --> 00:33:58,480
The horse's head on the butcher's has lost an ear.

412
00:33:58,520 --> 00:34:01,920
That's the florist laughing. He has crinkly eyes.

413
00:34:01,960 --> 00:34:04,920
In the bakery window there are lollipops!

414
00:34:04,960 --> 00:34:06,680
Mmm. Smell that.

415
00:34:06,720 --> 00:34:08,880
They're giving out melon slices.

416
00:34:10,480 --> 00:34:12,840
Sugarplum ice cream!

417
00:34:12,880 --> 00:34:15,440
We're passing the pork butcher.

418
00:34:15,480 --> 00:34:17,800
Ham, 79 francs. Spareribs, 45!

419
00:34:17,840 --> 00:34:22,480
Now the cheese shop. Picodons are 12.90, cabecous 23.50.

420
00:34:22,520 --> 00:34:26,920
At the butcher's a baby's watching a dog that's watching the chickens roasting.

421
00:34:26,960 --> 00:34:30,240
Now we're at the newspaper kiosk by the métro.

422
00:34:30,280 --> 00:34:32,280
I'll leave you here. Bye.

423
00:35:21,640 --> 00:35:23,840
"She can't relate to other people."

424
00:35:25,960 --> 00:35:28,720
"She was always a lonely child."

425
00:35:31,560 --> 00:35:34,400
On a sparkling evening in July,

426
00:35:34,440 --> 00:35:37,200
while on the beaches holidaymakers

427
00:35:37,240 --> 00:35:39,720
relax in the new-found sun,

428
00:35:39,760 --> 00:35:42,200
and in Paris the sweltering crowds

429
00:35:42,240 --> 00:35:44,520
gaze at the first bursts

430
00:35:44,560 --> 00:35:47,120
of the traditional fireworks, Amélie Poulain,

431
00:35:47,160 --> 00:35:50,760
godmother of outcasts,

432
00:35:50,800 --> 00:35:53,200
Madonna of the unloved,

433
00:35:53,240 --> 00:35:55,320
finally succumbs to exhaustion.

434
00:35:55,360 --> 00:35:59,920
In Paris' grief-stricken streets,

435
00:35:59,960 --> 00:36:02,680
a vast throng of mourners

436
00:36:02,720 --> 00:36:05,720
line her funeral route in silence

437
00:36:05,760 --> 00:36:10,040
with the measureless sorrow of newly orphaned children.

438
00:36:11,040 --> 00:36:13,080
What a strange destiny for one

439
00:36:13,120 --> 00:36:14,480
who gave her all,

440
00:36:14,520 --> 00:36:19,960
yet took such joy in life's simple pleasures.

441
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:23,480
Like Don Quixote, she pitted herself

442
00:36:23,520 --> 00:36:26,560
against the grinding windmill of all life's miseries.

443
00:36:38,480 --> 00:36:40,480
It was a losing battle

444
00:36:40,520 --> 00:36:42,440
that claimed her life too soon.

445
00:36:42,480 --> 00:36:44,680
At barely 23, Amélie Poulain

446
00:36:44,720 --> 00:36:48,200
let her young, tired body merge

447
00:36:48,240 --> 00:36:51,520
with the ebb and flow of universal woe.

448
00:36:51,560 --> 00:36:57,560
As she went, she felt a stab of regret for letting her father die

449
00:36:57,600 --> 00:37:01,040
without trying to give his stifled life

450
00:37:01,080 --> 00:37:05,160
the breath of air she had given

451
00:37:05,200 --> 00:37:07,200
to so many others.

452
00:39:17,880 --> 00:39:18,880
Wait!

453
00:39:23,720 --> 00:39:25,440
Wait!

454
00:39:28,200 --> 00:39:29,200
Wait...

455
00:39:30,520 --> 00:39:31,520
Wait, wait!

456
00:40:16,200 --> 00:40:21,360
Pages full of dud ID photos torn up and discarded by their owners,

457
00:40:21,440 --> 00:40:24,920
carefully reassembled by some oddball.

458
00:40:25,960 --> 00:40:27,920
Some family album!

459
00:40:31,920 --> 00:40:33,440
A pack of Gauloises.

460
00:40:33,520 --> 00:40:37,400
Just a second. It's so smoky in here. Can you tell me where they are?

461
00:40:37,480 --> 00:40:40,040
- I can't see a thing. - More to the left.

462
00:40:40,080 --> 00:40:41,640
- There? - A bit more. There.

463
00:40:44,400 --> 00:40:46,600
Thank you. You need change.

464
00:40:46,680 --> 00:40:48,960
Forget it.

465
00:40:49,040 --> 00:40:50,920
- Yes? - A mauresque.

466
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:53,360
A mauresque for the young man.

467
00:40:53,440 --> 00:40:56,680
One kir aligoté, one mauresque, and two mint sodas.

468
00:40:56,760 --> 00:40:59,880
Was that prenuptial or post-coital smooching?

469
00:40:59,960 --> 00:41:01,920
Is your bullshit congenital?

470
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:05,840
- Prenuptial. - Don't worry.

471
00:41:05,920 --> 00:41:07,880
You'll find Mr. Right one day.

472
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:12,120
All women want to sleep on a man's shoulder. All of them.

473
00:41:12,200 --> 00:41:16,800
All men snore after a few drinks, and I have a musical ear.

474
00:41:16,880 --> 00:41:20,440
I had an operation on my nasal cavities.

475
00:41:20,520 --> 00:41:22,480
I see you're a born romantic.

476
00:41:24,240 --> 00:41:26,880
I see you've never known true love.

477
00:41:28,160 --> 00:41:30,600
I did. It shortened my leg.

478
00:41:32,080 --> 00:41:36,360
- I thought you fell off a horse. - I did.

479
00:41:36,440 --> 00:41:38,800
I was in love with a trapeze artist.

480
00:41:38,880 --> 00:41:42,000
I should have known. They always drop you at the last minute.

481
00:41:42,080 --> 00:41:44,640
He dropped me just before my act.

482
00:41:46,680 --> 00:41:50,120
It floored me. And the horse.

483
00:41:50,200 --> 00:41:53,080
With me under it.

484
00:41:54,960 --> 00:41:57,200
The mauresque?

485
00:41:57,280 --> 00:42:00,080
Still, true love does exist.

486
00:42:00,120 --> 00:42:03,880
I'm not saying it doesn't. After 30 years behind this bar,

487
00:42:03,960 --> 00:42:07,480
I'm an expert. I can even give you the recipe.

488
00:42:09,720 --> 00:42:12,360
Take two regulars.

489
00:42:12,400 --> 00:42:15,520
Let each think the other fancies them. Leave it to simmer.

490
00:42:15,600 --> 00:42:17,400
It never fails.

491
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:27,120
Excuse me!

492
00:42:27,200 --> 00:42:28,840
Excuse me.

493
00:42:28,920 --> 00:42:30,640
- I've had enough. - I'll go.

494
00:42:34,160 --> 00:42:36,120
Haven't you hurt enough people?

495
00:42:39,800 --> 00:42:41,360
Gina can defend herself.

496
00:42:41,440 --> 00:42:44,560
I don't mean Gina. I mean Georgette.

497
00:42:47,640 --> 00:42:48,600
Georgette?

498
00:42:48,680 --> 00:42:51,640
Open your eyes! She craves your attention

499
00:42:51,680 --> 00:42:53,400
but you only have eyes for Gina.

500
00:42:55,560 --> 00:42:58,760
Poor girl! The things she does

501
00:42:58,800 --> 00:43:00,760
to catch your eye!

502
00:43:03,240 --> 00:43:05,200
You really must be blind.

503
00:43:13,560 --> 00:43:15,520
I'm off on a date. Bye!

504
00:43:15,600 --> 00:43:17,600
Goodbye.

505
00:43:19,800 --> 00:43:22,080
Whoever her new one is,

506
00:43:22,120 --> 00:43:25,560
he can't be worse than that nut with his tape recorder.

507
00:43:26,720 --> 00:43:28,560
Joseph's not so nutty.

508
00:43:29,560 --> 00:43:31,240
He's just in pain.

509
00:43:31,280 --> 00:43:34,160
Come off it, Amélie. They split up two months ago.

510
00:43:34,200 --> 00:43:37,360
To keep on coming here every day, he must be a masochist.

511
00:43:37,400 --> 00:43:40,320
Don't say you haven't noticed.

512
00:43:41,960 --> 00:43:43,080
Noticed what?

513
00:43:43,160 --> 00:43:45,920
He always sits here, right?

514
00:43:45,960 --> 00:43:47,440
Yes.

515
00:43:47,480 --> 00:43:48,800
Sit down.

516
00:43:49,800 --> 00:43:51,000
Sit down, Georgette.

517
00:43:53,240 --> 00:43:56,200
- What can you see? - My cigarette counter.

518
00:43:57,200 --> 00:43:59,320
And nothing's missing?

519
00:43:59,360 --> 00:44:00,320
No.

520
00:44:01,440 --> 00:44:02,840
Make an effort.

521
00:44:09,560 --> 00:44:11,360
I don't get it!

522
00:44:12,400 --> 00:44:14,880
I'll leave you to think about it. Good night.

523
00:44:30,920 --> 00:44:33,680
Good morning.

